Backtracking is one of the core algorithmic techniques used in problems involving:

searching

combinatorics

permutations

subsets

combinations

paths

constraint satisfaction

It works by trying out all possibilities but undoing (backtracking) choices when they lead to invalid solutions.

Below is the best, cleanest explanation for interviews.

🔥 1. What is Backtracking?
Backtracking = DFS + Undo + Pruning

It is a technique in which you:

Choose (make a decision)

Explore (go deeper recursively)

Unchoose (undo the decision → backtrack)

This allows exploring all valid solutions while avoiding useless paths.

🔥 2. General Template (VERY IMPORTANT)

Every backtracking solution follows this pattern:

void backtrack(Path current, Options options) {

    if (goalReached(current)) {
        addSolution(current);
        return;
    }

    for (option in options) {

        if (invalid(option))
            continue;

        apply(option);      // choose
        backtrack(current); // explore
        undo(option);       // unchoose
    }
}


This template works for permutations, combinations, subsets, N-Queens, graphs, etc.

🔥 3. Real Meaning (Simple Example)

Example: generate all subsets of {1,2,3}.

Decisions:

Include element?

Not include element?

Tree:

                     []
                 /         \
             [1]           []
            /   \         /  \
        [1,2]  [1]     [2]    []


Each path represents a subset.

🔥 4. Why Backtracking Works?

Because at each step we:

Try all possibilities

Reject paths that cannot lead to a solution

Revert changes to explore another branch

Backtracking cuts down massive search spaces.

🔥 5. Classic Problems Using Backtracking
Problem	Why Backtracking
Permutations of array	Try each element as next position
Combinations (n choose k)	Try choosing/not choosing
Subsets of array	Binary include/exclude tree
N-Queens	Try each column for each row; prune invalid
Sudoku	Try 1–9 for each cell; backtrack on conflict
Rat in a maze	Try each direction; backtrack on wall
Word search	Try all directions in matrix
Generate Parentheses	BFS with constraints
Knight’s Tour	Try all moves and backtrack failed paths
🔥 6. Example Codes (Simple & Interview-Ready)
(A) Permutations (Backtracking)
public List<List<Integer>> permute(int[] nums) {
    List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
    backtrack(nums, new ArrayList<>(), result);
    return result;
}

private void backtrack(int[] nums, List<Integer> tempList, List<List<Integer>> result) {
    if (tempList.size() == nums.length) {
        result.add(new ArrayList<>(tempList));
        return;
    }

    for (int num : nums) {
        if (tempList.contains(num)) continue; // pruning

        tempList.add(num);       // choose
        backtrack(nums, tempList, result); // explore
        tempList.remove(tempList.size() - 1); // unchoose
    }
}

(B) Subsets
public List<List<Integer>> subsets(int[] nums) {
    List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
    backtrack(0, nums, new ArrayList<>(), result);
    return result;
}

private void backtrack(int start, int[] nums, List<Integer> temp, List<List<Integer>> result) {
    result.add(new ArrayList<>(temp));

    for (int i = start; i < nums.length; i++) {
        temp.add(nums[i]);
        backtrack(i + 1, nums, temp, result);
        temp.remove(temp.size() - 1);
    }
}

(C) N-Queens
public List<List<String>> solveNQueens(int n) {
    List<List<String>> result = new ArrayList<>();
    char[][] board = new char[n][n];
    for (char[] row : board) Arrays.fill(row, '.');

    backtrack(0, board, result);
    return result;
}

private void backtrack(int row, char[][] board, List<List<String>> result) {
    if (row == board.length) {
        result.add(construct(board));
        return;
    }

    for (int col = 0; col < board.length; col++) {
        if (isSafe(board, row, col)) {
            board[row][col] = 'Q';
            backtrack(row + 1, board, result);
            board[row][col] = '.'; // undo
        }
    }
}

🔥 7. Key Points Asked in Interviews
✔ What is backtracking?

A refined DFS with pruning.

✔ What are 3 steps?

Choose → Explore → Unchoose.

✔ How to prune?

Skip invalid paths early using conditions.

✔ Time complexity?

Often exponential:

Permutations → O(n!)

Subsets → O(2ⁿ)

N-Queens → O(n!)

✔ When to use it?

When the problem requires “explore all possibilities but constraints prune search”.

🔥 8. Visualizing Backtracking (VERY IMPORTANT)

Imagine a tree.
Each node = a partial solution.
Edges = choices.
Backtracking explores all branches, but backs up when no solution ahead.

